  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Configuring the repository requires iteration. The Administrator should configure&amp;nbsp;the repository&amp;nbsp;and then&#xD;
    allow the users to spend time with the Asset Repository.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A collection of artifacts can be used to define the configuration, such as models, and Asset Type Specifications, and&#xD;
    Asset Workflow Specifications. These artifacts should be used to refine the repository configuration.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The Administrator should consider creating a special place in the Asset Repository to store policies and other guidance&#xD;
    the users need to follow, as shown in the figure below. For example, the Asset Versioning Policy, Asset Workflow&#xD;
    Specifications, Asset Type Specifications, and so forth should be stored. The set of assets stored here are to benefit&#xD;
    both Asset Consumers and Asset Producers in their understanding of the organization of the repository and how to work&#xD;
    with it.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img style=&quot;WIDTH: 728px; HEIGHT: 166px&quot; height=&quot;163&quot; alt=&quot;An example of an asset repository configuration.&quot;&#xD;
    src=&quot;./resources/repos_config_assets.gif&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
